      "text": "2. Video Metadata DB(Cassandra DB)",
      "fontSize": 131.96742859711475,
      "fontFamily": 7,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. Video Metadata DB(Cassandra DB)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.15
    },
    {
      "id": "4a4KrpkXHNuVWUDA4D3QB",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -3150.354990101432,
      "y": 24914.59047200439,
      "width": 4857.658203125,
      "height": 2286.1144864186303,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2S",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1665476351,
      "version": 961,
      "versionNonce": 698980945,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1783334988824,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "- partitioned by videoId\n- As cassandra has Replication Factor and Consistent Hashing\n- store metadata on Multiple Node\n\nProblem: Hot \n    EX: \n        Suppose Funny Cat video get 100M requests\n            - Let say RF = 2 -> Node 5, Node 8 stores the video\n           - Means Node 5 is getting 50M req and Node 8 is also get 50M requests\n           - Here Only a small set of replicas (Node5 and Node8) own Video C, \n            while the rest of the cluster cannot help with that partition.\n            - here Node 5 and Node 8 becomes hot partitions\n\nSolution : \n    - store Metadata in Redis cache\n    - Video metadata is typically cached using the cache-aside pattern. \n    - On a cache miss, the service reads from Cassandra and populates Redis. \n    - When metadata changes, the service updates Cassandra and invalidates the corresponding cache entry. \n    - The next read repopulates the cache with fresh data. \n    - This keeps reads fast while maintaining consistency.",
      "fontSize": 91.44457945674522,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "- partitioned by videoId\n- As cassandra has Replication Factor and Consistent Hashing\n- store metadata on Multiple Node\n\nProblem: Hot \n    EX: \n        Suppose Funny Cat video get 100M requests\n            - Let say RF = 2 -> Node 5, Node 8 stores the video\n           - Means Node 5 is getting 50M req and Node 8 is also get 50M requests\n           - Here Only a small set of replicas (Node5 and Node8) own Video C, \n            while the rest of the cluster cannot help with that partition.\n            - here Node 5 and Node 8 becomes hot partitions\n\nSolution : \n    - store Metadata in Redis cache\n    - Video metadata is typically cached using the cache-aside pattern. \n    - On a cache miss, the service reads from Cassandra and populates Redis. \n    - When metadata changes, the service updates Cassandra and invalidates the corresponding cache entry. \n    - The next read repopulates the cache with fresh data. \n    - This keeps reads fast while maintaining consistency.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "V0Zxxz1JTVMbGwaeQN2Zv",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -3294.6215494093694,
      "y": 29508.167638821848,
      "width": 1824.5625921872038,
      "height": 181.4332223688188,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
